titlestmt.principal:
Editors: Morris Eaves, University of Rochester;
Robert Essick, University of California, Riverside; and
Joseph Viscomi , University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill

provenance.note:
Possibly the copy acquired by George Romney directly from Blake, c. 1795, and sold from his collection, Christie's, 9 May 1834, in lot 84+, added in pen and ink to at least one copy of the catalogue, with *The Marriage of Heaven and Hell*, possibly copy D (18s. to "Tiffin," possibly Walter E. Tiffin); probably one of the works by Blake acquired by Isaac D'Israeli no later than 1824 and certainly in his collection no later than 1835; 
                    inherited by his son, the Earl of Beaconsfield, in 1848.  Objects 1-5 (Bentley Plates 1, 2, 4-6) were separated from the others by 1856.  
                    Objects 6-17 (Bentley Plates 7-18) were sold from Beaconsfield's collection, Sotheby's, 20 March 1882, lot 57 (£8.5s. to the dealer James Bain, 
                    possibly acting for Bernard Buchanan Macgeorge); this group in the Macgeorge collection no later than 1892.  Objects 1-5 (Bentley Plates 1, 2, 4-6) were sold anonymously at a Hodgson's auction, 
                    London, 14 Jan. 1904, lot 225 (£80 to Hopkins, possibly a dealer acting for Macgeorge).  The two groups of plates were reunited in the Macgeorge collection 
                    no later than 1906; the whole copy sold from his collection, Sotheby's, 1 July 1924, lot 116 (£500 to the dealer Gabriel Wells, possibly acting for George C. Smith); 
                    in Smith's collection no later than 1927; sold from his collection, Parke-Bernet, New York, 2 Nov. 1938, lot 26 ($13,000 to the dealer Charles Sessler, 
                    possibly acting for Moncure Biddle); in Biddle's collection no later than 1939; sold by Biddle through the dealer Thomas J. Gannon to Paul Mellon in 1948; 
                    given by Mellon to the Yale Center for British Art in 1992.
